******
[2]
Date: Wed 31 Oct 2018
Source: Oil City News [edited]
https://oilcitywyo.com/health/2018/10/31/increased-syphilis-cases-reported-in-wyoming/


Officials with the Wyoming Department of Health (WDH) say that they have detected an alarming increase in reported syphilis cases across Wyoming, especially in Fremont County. In a written statement, officials with the WDH say that there have been 34 Wyoming cases reported so far in 2018, which represents a 36% increase over last year's [2017] total for the entire year. With a reported 38% of this year's [2018] cases, Fremont County is an area of current concern. "Because of this increase, the department recently sent an alert to healthcare providers across the state encouraging them to promote testing and treatment with patients," said Courtney Smith, Communicable Disease Surveillance Program Manager with WDH.

Having multiple sex partners, sex without a condom, or anonymous sex partners are risks connected with this recent increase. Actions recommended by WDH include abstinence, limiting the number of sexual partners, correct and consistent condom use, and getting tested before starting a new sexual relationship. To learn more about the risk behaviors for syphilis infection, visit <www.knowyo.org> or contact a medical professional. The site provides voucher codes for no or low-cost syphilis, gonorrhea, chlamydia, HIV and hepatitis testing.

Genital sores caused by syphilis also make it easier to transmit and acquire HIV infection. "There is an estimated 2- to 5-fold increased risk of acquiring HIV if exposed when syphilis is present," Smith said. "Fortunately, the same steps you can take to decrease your risk of syphilis infection can also reduce your risk for HIV and other [sexually transmitted infections]."

