[Primary and secondary (P&S) syphilis are the symptomatic, contagious, earliest stages of infection, and indicate newly acquired infection. In 2017, the latest year for which data are available, the western region of the USA had the highest rate of reported P&S syphilis cases (13.2 cases per 100 000 population), followed by the South (9.7 cases per 100 000 population), the Northeast (8.0 cases per 100 000 population), and the Midwest (6.2 cases per 100 000 population) (https://www.cdc.gov/std/stats17/syphilis.htm). During 2016 to 2017, the P&S syphilis rate increased 16.8% in the West, 10.2% in the South, and 8.8% in the Midwest; the rate did not change in the Northeast.

In 2017, rates of reported P&S syphilis cases per 100 000 population ranged by state from 0.7 in Wyoming to 20.0 in Nevada; it was 40.4 in the District of Columbia and 1.8 in Alaska (https://www.cdc.gov/std/stats17/syphilis.htm). During 2016 to 2017, P&S syphilis rates increased in 36 of 50 of states.

As observed in prior years, in 2017 the rate of reported P&S syphilis cases in men (16.9 cases per 100 000 males) was much higher than in women (2.3 cases per 100 000 females), and men accounted for a large majority (87.7%) of P&S syphilis cases (https://www.cdc.gov/std/stats17/syphilis.htm). Among men, the rate of P&S syphilis has increased every year since 2000, and during 2016 to 2017, the rate among men increased 9.0%. In contrast, the P&S syphilis rate among women increased substantially (155.6%) since 2013.

Men who have sex with men (MSM) continued to account for the majority (57.9%) of P&S syphilis cases in 2017. During 2016 to 2017, the number of cases increased 8.6% among MSM, 17.8% among men who have sex with women (MSW), and 24.9% among women. Among 2017 P&S syphilis cases with known HIV status, 45.5% of cases among MSM were HIV-positive, compared with 8.8% of cases among MSW and 4.5% of cases among women.

Paralleling increases in P&S syphilis among women, the rate of reported congenital syphilis has increased each year since 2012. In 2017, there were 918 reported cases of congenital syphilis, including 64 syphilitic stillbirths and 13 infant deaths, and the national rate was 23.3 cases per 100 000 live births, a 153.3% increase relative to 2013 (9.2 cases per 100 000 live births).

The 1st news article above reports that the syphilis outbreak in the US state of Alaska is occurring mostly among MSM in Anchorage, a city with an estimated 301 826 residents in 2017; Anchorage is the most populous city in the state, located in the south-central portion of Alaska (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anchorage,_Alaska). A map of Alaska showing the location of Anchorage can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/Anchorage,+AK.

The 2nd news article above reports that the syphilis outbreak in the US state of Wyoming is concentrated in Fremont County, which is located in the central-western portion of the state; the county, with a population of about 40 000 residents, is roughly the size of the US state of Vermont and is a gateway into Yellowstone National Park and Grand Teton National Park (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fremont_County,_Wyoming). The Wind River Reservation, which constitutes just over one-third of Fremont County's area, is home to the Eastern Shoshone and Northern Arapaho Native American tribes; American Indians constitute about 20% of the county's population (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wind_River_Indian_Reservation). A map that shows the location of Fremont County can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/Fremont+County,+WY. - Mod.ML

